{{Infobox officeholder | name = Bill Harrison | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | order = | office = Mayor of Fremont, California | term_start = December 2012 | term_end = December 2016 | predecessor = [[Gus Morrison]] | successor = Lily Mei | party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] }}
'''Bill Harrison''' is an American accountant and politician who was the mayor of [[Fremont, California]], between December 2012 and December 2016, succeeding appointed mayor [[Gus Morrison]].
== Background and career == He was born and raised in Fremont, is a graduate of [[University of California, Santa Barbara]], and is a [[certified public accountant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremont.gov/701/Bill-Harrison-Mayor |title=Bill Harrison, Mayor |website=City of Fremont official website |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>
Prior to 2012,{{clarify|date=February 2018|reason=Starting when?}} Harrison was a city councilman. On November 6, 2012, Harrison out-polled four rivals to win the independently elected mayor's office with 34% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2012/11/06/ca/alm/race/015/ |title=Mayor; City of Fremont Election Information November 6, 2012 Election |website=Smartvoter.org |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>
== Initiatives and positions == * Harrison promoted [[Economic Development Incentives|business incentive]]s to manufacturers, in particular companies associated with nearby [[Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/fremont/ci_26649903/fremont-gains-reputation-silicon-valley-manufacturing-hub |title=Fremont gains reputation as Silicon Valley manufacturing hub |work=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> * He supported [[Tesla Motors]]' plan for a controversial outsized billboard at its Fremont plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_26418717/tesla-proposing-giant-billboard-fremont-factory-880 |title=2014: Gigabillboard? Tesla proposes enormous sign outside Fremont factory |work=San Jose Mercury News |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> * He also presided over redevelopment efforts centered on changing Fremont from a [[suburb]]an city to an urban [[Central business district|hub]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mohammed |first=Aliyah |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/fremont/ci_26514267/demolition-heralds-future-fremont-downtown |title=Demolition heralds future Fremont Downtown |work=San Jose Mercury News |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>
