{{Infobox business park | name = Pacific Shores Center | image = File:Pacific Shores Center 04 of 23.jpg | image_upright = | alt = View of buildings facing Greco Island | caption = View of buildings facing [[Greco Island]] | map_type = San Francisco Bay Area#California#USA | relief = | map_size = 235 | map_dot_label = Pacific Shores Center | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = Redwood City, California | address = 1700 Seaport Blvd, Redwood City, CA 94063 | coordinates = {{coord|37.51153|-122.20288|region:US-CA_type:landmark_scale:40000|format=dms|display=it}} | opening_date = {{start date and age|2001}} | closing_date = | developer = [[Jay Paul Company]] | construction_cost = {{currency|500million|USD}} | manager = | owner = [[Informatica]], [[Google]], DivcoWest | architect = DES Architects + Engineers | number_of_tenants = | number_of_workers = | size = {{convert|106|acre}} | parking = 4000 | website = {{Official URL}} | footnotes = }}
'''Pacific Shores Center''' is a [[High tech|high-tech]] [[business park]] located in [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]], [[California]], adjacent to the [[Port of Redwood City]].
==History== The property that Pacific Shores Center was developed on had many uses through the years from part of the Redwood City Harbor Company to cement production to being part of saltworks with [[Leslie Salt]].<ref name="bcdc">{{cite web|author1=San Francisco Bay Conservation and Development Commission|authorlink1=San Francisco Bay Conservation and Development Commission|title=Review of Port Priority Use Areas and Marine Terminal Designations in the San Francisco Bay Area Seaport Plan|url=http://www.bcdc.ca.gov/planning/reports/ReviewOfPortPriorityUseAreasAndMarineTerminalDesignationsInTheSFBayAreaSeaportPlan_June1994.pdf|accessdate=6 March 2017|date=3 June 1994}}</ref> In {{Date|1990}} the [[Teachers' Retirement System of the State of Illinois]] bought {{convert|116|acre}} of land adjacent to the Port of Redwood City and [[Westpoint Slough]] and formed the Pacific Shores Center Partnership to develop it.<ref name="biz1999">{{cite news|last1=Graebner|first1=Lynn|title=Table finally set for huge Redwood City project|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/1999/08/02/story4.html|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=Silicon Valley Business Journal|publisher=[[The Business Journals]]|date=1 Aug 1999}}</ref><ref name="openc">{{cite web|title=PACIFIC SHORES CENTER LIMITED PARTNERSHIP|url=https://opencorporates.com/companies/us_de/2249694|website=[[OpenCorporates]]|accessdate=6 March 2017|date=20 December 2016}}</ref> After many years of planning Redwood City and the partnership had a complete development agreement with plans for a land swap, that decreased the total property to {{convert|106|acre}}, and public shore space to allow for public use of parts of the property.<ref name="rwcagmt">{{cite web|author1=[[Redwood City]]|title=Development Agreement|url=http://documents.redwoodcity.org/publicweblink/DocView.aspx?dbid=0&id=17824&cr=1|website=Redwood City Documents|accessdate=6 March 2017|date=26 October 1998}}</ref> In {{Date|November 1999}} [[Jay Paul Company]] entered into an agreement to buy the rights for the project by outbidding several other competing developers with a {{currency|90million|USD}} bid.<ref name="90mil">{{cite news|last1=Robson|first1=Douglas|title=Peninsula land fetches $90M|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/1999/11/29/story1.html|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=San Francisco Business Times|publisher=[[The Business Journals]]|date=28 November 1999}}</ref> By early 2000 with the buildings not even complete; [[Excite#Excite.40Home|Excite@Home]], [[Openwave|Phone.com]], [[Informatica|Informatica Corp]], and [[Broadvision|BroadVision Inc.]] had all signed leases. Demand at the time caused rent prices to increase for the center as well.<ref name="biz2000">{{cite news|author1=Lynn Graebner|author2=Douglas Robson|title=Big Peninsula project nearly full before it starts|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2000/03/13/story5.html|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=San Francisco Business Times|publisher=[[The Business Journals]]|date=12 March 2000}}</ref> At this time there were plans for a ferry service to connect [[San Francisco]] and [[Alameda, California]] to an adjacent ferry terminal to mitigate traffic concerns at the time with so many of the expected workers to be projected commuting.<ref name="ferry2000">{{cite news|last1=Pence|first1=Angelica|title=Redwood City Seaway / Peninsula port hopes to offer ferry service to S.F., East Bay|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Redwood-City-Seaway-Peninsula-port-hopes-to-3304073.php|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[SF Gate]]|date=3 July 2000}}</ref>
By {{Date|April 2002}} the burst of the [[Dot-com bubble]] had decreased demand for office space and the center previously estimated to fill completely was sitting with a vacancy rate of 65%.<ref name="vacancy">{{cite news|last1=Jimenez|first1=Jorge|title=New Tenant at Pacific Shores|url=https://www.costar.com/News/Article/New-Tenant-at-Pacific-Shores/38266|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[CoStar Group]]|date=23 April 2002}}</ref> However fortunes changed and in late 2006 the campus was sold from Jay Paul to [[Starwood Capital Group]] for over {{currency|800million|USD}} for the center which had hit 90% capacity. Tenants at the time included [[Eidos Interactive]], [[PDL BioPharma]], [[DreamWorks Animation]], Threshold Pharmaceutical, Openwave, [[Symantec]], and engineering firm [[Rudolph and Sletten]].<ref name="sale2006">{{cite news|last1=Conrad|first1=Katherine|title=Pacific Shores Center sold for about $800M|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2006/12/13/pacific-shores-center-sold-for-about-800m/|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[East Bay Times]]|date=13 December 2006}}</ref> The following year two of the buildings, specifically the ones PDL BioPharma was located within, were sold to Shorenstein Properties for an undisclosed sum, for the first time making Pacific Shores Center to have more than one owner.<ref name="sale2007">{{cite news|last1=Hollis|first1=Robert|title=DEAL OF THE WEEK: 1400-1500 Seaport Blvd., Redwood City / Shorenstein buys more office space|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/DEAL-OF-THE-WEEK-1400-1500-Seaport-Blvd-2600151.php|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[SF Gate]]|date=24 April 2007}}</ref> [[San Mateo County]] filed a lawsuit in August 2009 over a tax dispute with the Center. County officials claimed that the sale of property in 2006 never had the property transfer taxes paid while the Center argued over the county tax code.<ref name="salesuit">{{cite news|last1=Bishop|first1=Shaun|title=San Mateo County sues office complex owners in tax dispute|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2009/08/20/san-mateo-county-sues-office-complex-owners-in-tax-dispute-2/|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=20 August 2009}}</ref>
Starwood Capital ran into issues with overdue debt in {{Date|2012}} and brought in [[The Blackstone Group|Blackstone]] with an ownership stake. Starwood also sold off two of the buildings at the complex to Informatica for {{currency|148.5million|USD}}.<ref name="blackstone">{{cite news|last1=Sadovi|first1=Maura Webber|title=Pacific Shores Positioning|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203833004577249730377746176|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=29 February 2012}}</ref> In {{Date|2014}}, [[Google]] bought the six buildings, over half the center, at {{convert|934200|sqft}} of office space, which Starwood and Blackstone owned, for {{currency|585million|USD}}.<ref name="googlebuy">{{cite web|author1=Hui-yong Yu|author2=Brian Womack|title=Google Grows With $1.6 Billion in California Office Deals|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-10-25/google-grows-with-1-6-billion-in-california-office-deals|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|accessdate=8 March 2017|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> Shortly after Google's purchase, Shorenstein Properties sold the two buildings they owned to DivcoWest Properties for about {{currency|260million|USD}}. This has left Pacific Shores Center with fragmented ownership to this day with the three owners all with different sections.<ref name="divco">{{cite news|last1=Donato-Weinstein|first1=Nathan|title=Two more buildings sell at Pacific Shores, but not to Google|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2014/11/03/two-more-buildings-sell-at-pacific-shores-but-not.html|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=Silicon Valley Business Journal|publisher=[[The Business Journals]]|date=3 November 2014}}</ref>
==Other== Pacific Shores Center is used more than just as an area for work. The facilities present include a {{convert|38000|sqft}} fitness center that includes a gym, pool, and spa along with playing fields.<ref name="googlebuy"/> Public shore access allows for people to park and walk along the Westpoint Slough on a section of the [[San Francisco Bay Trail]].<ref name="bcdc"/>
The annual [[Stanford University]] Treeathlon [[triathlon]] competition is hosted in part at the center along with the Westpoint Harbor.<ref name="treeathalon">{{cite news|last1=Laman|first1=Anna|title=Triathlon team to host 700 competitors in 12th annual Treeathlon|url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2016/03/04/triathlon-team-to-host-700-competitors-in-12th-annual-treeathlon/|accessdate=8 March 2017|work=[[The Stanford Daily]]|date=4 March 2016}}</ref>
